{"title":"Grounded Video Description","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Video captioning models often hallucinate objects and are not explicitly grounded in visual evidence, partly due to the lack of video datasets that link language to localized objects.","method":"They introduce ActivityNet-Entities, augmenting ActivityNet Captions with noun-phrase–to–bounding-box annotations in videos. Each concrete noun phrase is grounded with a box in one representative frame per segment, including co-references and group annotations. The dataset provides 51.8k annotated segments with 157.8k boxes and converts phrases to 432 single-word object labels via a frequency threshold, enabling both training with box supervision and evaluation via attention/grounding localization metrics (Attn., Grd., F1_all, F1_loc)."},{"problem":"Captioning systems need to generate sentences that are visually grounded, linking object words to specific regions in video frames rather than relying on priors.","method":"They propose a grounded video description model jointly optimizing language generation with three grounding supervisions: supervised region attention (to attend to the correct proposal when producing a visual word), region classification over proposals, and sentence-conditioned object grounding (localization) losses. The model builds grounding-aware region encodings by concatenating detector region features, a region–class similarity matrix (initialized by transferring classifiers from a Visual Genome–pretrained detector via GloVe-based nearest-class mapping), and spatio-temporal location embeddings, followed by a self-attention layer to model object interactions. Language decoding uses temporal attention (Bi-GRU context) and region attention; class probabilities are conditioned on the attention state as a semantic prior for grounding. This yields large gains in grounding accuracy (e.g., from ~22% to ~43% on GT sentences) and improved caption quality, setting state-of-the-art on video and image description benchmarks."}]}
